<subSubSection id="C341656EFFBBFF88A0A074F5F5BCFBBA" pageId="5" pageNumber="27" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BE436E5FFBBFF88A0A074F5F4E1FF63" blockId="5.[136,1452,158,1121]" box="[136,1424,158,185]" pageId="5" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis id="B92FEAF7FFBBFF88A0A074F5F071FF63" box="[136,256,158,184]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="27">Etymology</emphasis>
:—Species epithet based on the Tianshan Mountain in 
<collectingRegion id="499FF807FFBBFF88A34B74F5F2B9FF63" box="[867,968,158,184]" country="China" name="Xinjiang Uygur" pageId="5" pageNumber="27">Xinjiang</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F34C7675FFBBFF88A3FB74F5F568FF63" box="[979,1049,158,184]" name="China" pageId="5" pageNumber="27">China</collectingCountry>
, where the species was collected.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE436E5FFBBFF88A09574A8F5DEFEDB" blockId="5.[136,1452,158,1121]" pageId="5" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis id="B92FEAF7FFBBFF88A09574A8F05EFF07" box="[189,303,195,220]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="27">Diagnosis</emphasis>
:—Characterized by fairly inconspicuous, cottony-woolly ring, red to brownish-red scales gradually thinning out towards the marginal zone on the pileus, rarely clamped, guttulated basidiospores.
</paragraph>
